Content: "SEOUL (Reuters) - U.S. President Donald Trump on Friday said South Korea should heed advice from U.S. intelligence and security officials over North Korea’s nuclear threat as he criticized South Korea’s military buildup in response to that threat. Trump’s comments came after South Korea’s president called for the deployment of U.S. nuclear-capable missiles to South Korea to counter the growing threat facing the United States.    Trump’s comments came as Seoul was nearing completion of a missile defense system known as Terminal High Altitude Area Defense that analysts say would put a powerful missile on every square meter of South Korean territory where Seoul has a long coastline.  Trump, who spoke about South Korea’s leadership by referring to the threat with North Korea’s threats, said, “South Korea has to step up and understand what has happened in the past because they have a responsibility for that.”  In a tweet, he added, “this is a strong reminder that our allies and partners are united in their resolve and resolve to make sure that this nuclear threat stays.” Trump’s comments underscore fears among U.S. allies over North Korea’s nuclear program which has not been formally verified and is believed to be far more advanced than what they have previously acknowledged.   The Trump administration has been sharply critical of sanctions against Russia and China over its own nuclear tests, and has been concerned about China’s military assertiveness in the South China Sea and South China itself’s disputed artificial islands in the strategically important waterway. In the past Trump has said South Korea must toughen its security and has threatened to unleash U.S. forces to protect the United States if it threatened the United States with military action.      Trump’s comments come as tensions escalate with North Korea over its recent missile tests and bellicose statements, with U.S. Secretary of State Rex Tillerson scheduled to visit South Korea for Saturday. 